element.name: Clearing & Settlement Engine
element.documentation: ##### Function IT-capability that supports clearing and settlement of transactions ##### Context Clearing denotes all activities from the time a commitment is made for a transaction until it is settled. Settlement is the actual execution of the transaction and all the accompanying activities. Clearing of payments turns the promise of payment into actual movement of money from one bank to another. The settlement is the actual movement of money, the money-exchange step. Payments Clearing and Settlement in bulk and/or per transaction can be used: 1] within ING to clear and settle between entities internally (is part of the coverage of the Payment Engine), 2] in- and external at the same time when also third Banks (FI's = Financial Institutions) can participate in the Clearing and Settlement circle, 3] for a Clearing and Settlement organisation to function as (Pan European) Automated Clearing House. Securities Settlement is a business process whereby securities or interests in securities are delivered, usually against (in simultaneous exchange for) payment of money, to fulfill contractual obligations, such as those arising under securities trades. Securities Clearing & Settlement includes support for: - Claiming in the market due to Corporate Actions on unsettled positions, - Daily reconciliation of trades with the Clearing. - Registration of the assignments received from the Clearing and assign the omnibus level accounts. - Inform customer side custody on assignments. - Sending and matching of external settlement instructions (as a result of executed orders within Market Order Management) and transfers received from customer side custody, - Capture the actual settlement as result of the settlement confirmation received from the custodian, - Informing customer order management on settlements and to be settled positions. properties={ "LAA": "Yes", "level": "3", "outline": "3.1.18", "label": "${property:outline} ${name}", "zOrder": "301180000", "uuid": "27e6ee49-715e-4c8b-8503-dd4096ee6cf6", "GUID": "id-1e749479-8d71-11ec-19bb-0050568bdf9a", "ARIS": "id-3684179d-8e35-11ec-289b-0050568b5c9f" };

element.name: Equity Risk (BB) Management
element.documentation: Ability to manage the risk of the exposure of a bank towards holding equity positions and its effect on the bank?s financial condition. Equity risk can be defined as market risk. By market risk, we denote the possibility of losses due to unfavourable market movements. For equity investments this can be due to the level of equity prices, volatility of these prices and dividends. In scope The product scope of equity risk management includes all equity activities originating from banking and - asset and liability management. The organizational scope includes ING Bank as well as ING Group. More specifically, the following risk/products are included in the scope of this policy: ? strategic positions in other financial institutions; ? strategic investment in FinTech; ? other investments managed by Corporate investments; ? other investments managed by other locations; ? Real Estate funds. Out of scope The following risk/products are excluded from the scope of this policy: ? Equity Risk in Trading books; ? ING Bank and ING Group own issued equity; ? Equity positions of which the underlying entity is fully consolidated; ? Equity instruments falling under the scope of credit or trading risk: ? Subordinated perpetual loans; ? Convertible bonds.

element.name: Investment Risk Management
element.documentation: Ability to set and oversee the procedure to identify, measure, monitor and control risks related to Investment portfolio management. Capital Investment risk reflects the risk of rate changes decreasing the value of the SWAPs held in order to swap floating rate income on capital invested with subsidiaries for a fixed rate income in an effort to reduce volatility. In case the bank would face an unexpected capital shortfall and would sell assets, these SWAPs would be sold at a value discount. Economic capital, then, is held to reflect these value losses. Group Treasury risk reflects the risk of losses on this interest rate position that ING strategically leaves open. For calculation of MREC for Treasury risk positions, the bank uses a HVaR-based approach.

element.name: Interest Rate Risk (BB) Management
element.documentation: Ability to set and oversee the procedure to identify, measure, monitor and control risks related to Interest management. Interest rate risk has two forms ? economic value volatility and earnings volatility. Earnings volatility represents the shortterm effect of interest rate changes on the profitability and therefore has a direct connection to the target Net Interest Margin. Economic value volatility on the other hand represents the long-term effects of the interest rate changes. As a typical interest rate transaction cannot stabilize both the economic value and earnings volatility, the management of both forms is complementary in understanding the scope of IRRBB. It is this combination that ensures ING will be able to deliver a stable Net Interest Margin both on the short and longer term. Convexity Risk The linear interest rate exposures in the portfolios with embedded options are hedged, leaving exposure to convexity risk, mainly caused by the prepayment risk, the offered rate risk, and the early withdrawal risk in the portfolios. Embedded options sold to customers, are hedged using a delta-hedging methodology (which is implicitly linear). This leaves an exposure to convexity and volatility risk. The MREC for Convexity risk must be calculated based on NPV profiles and simulated interest rate shifts. The NPV impact must be calculated for a large number of scenarios as defined in the EC - Convexity Risk model description Customer Behaviour Risk Interest rate sensitivities on mortgages and current/savings accounts are calculated with models that are based on several assumptions regarding customer behaviour. Customer Behaviour Risk (CBR) is the potential future value loss due to uncertainty in the behaviour of customers towards embedded options in commercial products, e.g., a mortgage prepayment option or an option to withdraw or deposit variable rate savings. The CBR is calculated by stressing the underlying assumptions in the models for behavioural assets and liabilities
